commit.message:
Combine used_attrs and used_names to avoid false positives

This fixes false positives when assigning to `x.some_name` but reading via `some_name`.
Note this produces false negatives in the opposite situation when `x.some_name` and `some_name` are different, so this is a trade-off in the direction of more precision / less sensitivity.

This direction is in line with pyflakes design principles: https://github.com/PyCQA/pyflakes#design-principles
> it will try very, very hard to never emit false positives.

Fixing this more accurately probably requires a lot more work to trace references and analyze context.

Fixes #221

Treat `getattr/hasattr(obj, "constant_string", ...)` as a reference to `obj.constant_string`

I realize handling `getattr` is a slippery slope. I think this case makes sense and is a reasonable place to draw the line.

My rationale is that the following code does the same thing, counts as a reference to obj.constant_string, but is not what most people would write.
```
try:
    x = obj.constant_string
except AttributeError:
    x = None
```
Update version number to 2.0 for release.

Parse mypy type comments

This prevents type-only imports from being flagged as unused.

Implementation decision note: As typed_ast will not be updated to support parsing Python 3.8+ syntax, I'm choosing not to use it. The downside of using Python's built-in type comment support is that it requires Python 3.8+. Someone more motivated than me could potentially make vulture use both, but I don't feel it's worth the complexity/effort given typed_ast seems likely to eventually die.

Fixes #152
See also #153
Fix: Logger.propagate is an instance attribute, not a class attribute.
Add short note about unreachable code to README.
Consider all files under test or tests directories test files.
